title: For Sale/Trade:  30 Gauge Mystery update
location: Lebanon, Ft. Leonard Wood, Springfield, Missouri
postcontent: Yes, 30 Gauge. I am stumped with this gun and have exhausted my research efforts.  I picked up this shotgun about four years to do further research on it.  The Miroku Model 100 or BC My Luck, was an early version single shot shotgun.  I have seen this gun in 12 gauge but never a 30 gauge.  In fact this is the ony shotgun I have seen in a 30 gauge. From my research I have found that the 30 gauge was a brass shotshell that was orginally used with blackpowder.  The chamber is shy of 3 inches as denoted by the 75mm marking under the barrel. There are some companies that are making brass shells however, I am not a gunsmith and would dare not make a determination if this was a shooter or not.  The lock up is tight and trigger, safety and action all work as intened.  Japan did make 30 and 32 gauge single shot guns for citizens to have as house guns when the Americans would invade.  These were junk guns and not Mirokus.  If you are intersted please shoot me an offer or if you have some info and would like to share please feel free to do so.  FYI there are Proof Marks visiable however, I cannot find them in my book.  I would estimate the date of manufacture around 1950s? Open to pawn shop Marlin/Glenfield .22 or cash.

When installed on a Suarez 319K slide, the clean and refined package looks like a complete Glock 34 slide, and will fit in most Glock 34 holsters.The Kompressor includes two ports on top, and an additional port on either side, for a total of four ports to stabilize the muzzle of your pistol during extended firing strings.
